Expanded Audit of Hopper Compared to
Pinocchio/Quasar and Revised Action Plan
This round of analysis examined portions of the Hopper zero‑copy state framework that
weren’t covered previously. In addition to the core crates (hopper‑core, hopper‑runtime,
hopper‑native), the inspection looked at supporting crates (hopper‑macros,
hopper‑macros‑proc), subsystem helpers (lazy, lens, project), domain‑specific examples
(finance, multisig, staking, vesting), and the program derivation and layout infrastructure.
We cross‑referenced Hopper’s design and unsoundness issues with Pinocchio and Quasar
and consulted Anchor’s official documentation to understand industry best practices for
zero‑copy types[1].
What’s new from this pass
VerifiedAccount and VerifiedAccountMut
 In the previous pass we suspected that VerifiedAccount::get and
VerifiedAccountMut::get/get_mut might be unsound because they return &T/&mut
T references. On closer inspection, these methods wrap the underlying byte slice in
either Ref/RefMut (borrow guard) or a raw slice at construction, and the guard is
held in the VerifiedBytes::Borrowed enum. Therefore the returned references
remain valid for the lifetime of the VerifiedAccount and the borrow guard is not
dropped prematurely. The design is safe so long as T: Pod + FixedLayout .
Projectable traits and lens API
 Hopper provides hopper_native::project and hopper_native::lens helpers to
read foreign program data. These rely on a custom Projectable marker trait that
only requires Copy + 'static. The project functions perform bounds and alignment
checks and optionally verify the account discriminator, then cast to &T/&mut T .
Because Projectable does not require bytemuck::Pod, the caller is responsible for
ensuring no padding bytes or invariants exist in the struct—otherwise undefined
behaviour is possible. The lens API is intentionally an escape hatch; it is safe for
reading simple primitives (u64, Pubkey), but for complex types the recommended
approach should be to require Pod + FixedLayout or supply a safe wrapper.
Anchoring the trait to Pod would align Hopper with Quasar and Anchor’s
#[account(zero_copy)] which automatically derives Copy, Zeroable, Pod and uses
#[repr(C)][1].
Header and layout infrastructure
 hopper‑runtime::layout defines a 16‑byte header (disc, version, flags, layout_id)
and the LayoutContract trait. This contract binds a type to its wire format and
includes compile‑time constants for discriminator, version, layout fingerprint and

wire size. Runtime checks call validate_header to confirm that accounts match
the expected discriminator and layout fingerprint.
 Tiered loading uses these contracts to produce
VerifiedAccount<T>/VerifiedAccountMut<T> wrappers that guarantee size and
layout correctness. This design is unique among frameworks; Pinocchio provides
only raw zero‑copy pointers, and Quasar uses layout‐free Account<T> objects.
Other crates and examples
 hopper‑finance, hopper‑lending, hopper‑staking, hopper‑multisig and
hopper‑vesting contain domain‑specific logic implemented on top of Hopper. They
rely on macros and the safe Ref/RefMut wrappers and do not introduce additional
unsound pointer casts.
 The lens module defines functions like read_address, read_le_u64 and
read_field::<T> which perform bounds checks and then cast to &T via
Projectable. This is safe when reading simple primitives but should be clearly
documented as unsafe for complex types.
Confirmation of previous findings
 The core unsoundness in hopper‑core::frame::segment_ref and segment_mut
remains: they take a Ref<[u8]>/RefMut<[u8]>, immediately drop the guard and
return a naked reference to T. This violates the borrow‑tracking discipline. The fix is
to return Ref<T>/RefMut<T> instead.
 Several APIs accept T: Copy rather than T: Pod + FixedLayout . This allows
misaligned or non‑plain‑old‑data types to be interpreted directly from bytes, risking
undefined behaviour. Restricting these to Pod + FixedLayout is necessary.
 The CLI still only supports hopper compile --emit rust and does not generate a
deployable program or IDL; this must be expanded to full build/test/deploy
functionality.
Revised and expanded recommendations
Building on the original recommendations, here is an updated action plan. Items prefaced
with (New) are newly identified or clarified from this round.
1. Return Ref<'_,T>/RefMut<'_,T> for all typed segment APIs
Fix: In hopper‑core::frame::segment_ref/segment_mut return Ref<'_,T> instead
of &T/&mut T . Propagate this change through any wrappers. This ties the lifetime of
the returned reference to the borrow guard and restores Hopper’s promised aliasing
safety. All typed reads and writes should therefore go through RAII guards like Ref
and RefMut. This pattern is already used in hopper‑runtime and is similar to
Quasar’s design.
2. Constrain safe overlays to Pod + FixedLayout
Fix: Where Hopper currently requires only T: Copy (e.g.,

hopper‑native::account_view::segment_ref, segment_mut, raw_ref, raw_mut,
and in hopper‑runtime::context), tighten the bounds to T: Pod + FixedLayout .
This ensures that only 1‑byte aligned, plain‑old‑data types can be overlaid on raw
bytes. In Anchor, zero‑copy accounts annotated with #[account(zero_copy)]
automatically derive Copy, Zeroable and Pod and use #[repr(C)][1]; Hopper should
provide the same guarantees.
3. Provide derive macros for Pod and layout
Fix: Extend hopper_layout! or add a #[hopper::pod] attribute so that user‑defined
structs automatically derive Pod, FixedLayout and a 1‑byte alignment. This can
mimic Anchor’s #[account(zero_copy)] which derives Copy, Zeroable, Pod and
uses #[repr(C)][2]. A macro like #[hopper::state] could also derive these traits
automatically. This reduces user error and ensures the safe traits are in place at
compile time.
4. Harmonize the API surface
Fix: Deprecate the legacy Frame API or make it call into the runtime’s safer
functions. There should be exactly one way to obtain typed segments: using
Ref/RefMut returned from the runtime. Remove any functions that return naked
references to T without a guard. Align project, lens and Projectable with Pod +
FixedLayout or clearly document them as unsafe escape hatches.
5. Expand compile‑fail and runtime test suites
Expand tests: Add compile‑fail tests to ensure: (a) overlapping segment borrows are
rejected, (b) non‑Pod types cannot be passed to typed segment APIs, (c) macros
reject missing #[repr(C)], wrong discriminators or duplicate account definitions,
(d) account‑owner mismatches throw errors, and (e) lens methods require explicit
acknowledgement of unsafety for custom structs. Quasar’s
lang/tests/compile_fail and Anchor’s macro tests provide examples of this.
6. Complete CLI and IDL generation
Fix: Finish the hopper-cli pipeline so that hopper build , hopper test , hopper
deploy work end‑to‑end. Build a .so program, run integration tests in a local
validator, and deploy to the network. Generate a JSON IDL similar to Anchor’s or
Quasar’s to describe account layouts, instruction metadata and segment
definitions. This will enable client code generation and integration in
TypeScript/Python.
7. Document unsafe surfaces thoroughly
Fix: Update docs/UNSAFE_INVARIANTS.md to enumerate every unsafe function, what
invariants it relies on, and the safe alternatives. Include examples of using
cast_unchecked and Projectable only in truly performance‑sensitive contexts.
Clarify that Projectable is essentially a Tier C escape hatch and that safe code
should rely on Pod + FixedLayout wherever possible.

8. Benchmark only after safety fixes are applied
Recommendation: Once the safe API is in place, re‑benchmark Hopper’s
compute‑unit consumption against Pinocchio and Quasar. Use realistic instruction
patterns (multiple segment borrows, CPIs) and document results. Anchor’s docs
highlight that zero‑copy can reduce deserialization cost by up to ~90% for large
accounts[3]; Hopper should only claim comparable or better performance when
using the corrected API.
9. Innovative directions and enhancements
10.Const‑generic segments & compile‑time offsets – Use const generics to define
segments as Segment::<OFFSET, SIZE> ; this would allow the compiler to fold
pointer arithmetic into constants, further reducing overhead.
11.Client code generation – Build a tool that reads Hopper’s layout manifest and
emits client code in Rust/TypeScript. Anchor’s IDL and Quasar’s manifest provide
guidance here; a Hopper client generator would significantly improve DX.
12.Dynamic borrow stack – Explore a borrow stack rather than a single byte counter in
each account. A small stack could model nested immutable/mutable borrows and
allow more flexible patterns without violating aliasing. This would support
non‑lexical borrows (e.g. temporarily releasing a borrow and reacquiring it) while
retaining deterministic CU cost.
13. Hybrid zero‑copy/serialization – Provide macros that allow certain fields to be
lazily deserialized (e.g. Vec<T>, String), while keeping adjacent fields zero‑copy.
Anchor warns that zero copy is not ideal for dynamic data[3]; a hybrid approach
would let developers trade performance for flexibility.
14.On‑chain schema versioning & migrations – Extend LayoutContract with version
negotiation and migration helpers. Allow safe reading of older versions and
upgrades to new versions. Provide macros to handle reserved bytes and extension
regions gracefully.
15.Integrated PDAs & bump optimizations – Provide macros similar to Anchor’s
seeds & bump constraints to allocate PDAs with the correct bump. Hopper already
exposes a BUMP_OFFSET optimization in macros; unify it with account creation
functions and test coverage.
16.Cross‑program lens improvements – Clarify the safety model of Projectable and
lens functions. Add a #[unsafe_projectable] attribute for cases where callers
want to accept the risks, and create safe lens functions that require Pod +
FixedLayout to encourage correct usage. Document that cross‑program reading of
unknown layouts should stick to simple types (Pubkey, u64) or use a manifest/IDL.
17. Education & examples
Expand docs: Add step‑by‑step tutorials (Vault, AMM, staking) demonstrating safe
segment access, cross‑program lens usage, and migrations. Provide narrative
examples comparing Hopper, Pinocchio and Quasar. Anchor’s docs include

guidelines on when to use zero‑copy (large accounts, order books) and when to
avoid it (small dynamic data structures)[3]; Hopper’s documentation should offer
similar advice.
Conclusion
This pass confirms that Hopper’s architecture has the potential to be a “best of all”
zero‑copy framework combining Pinocchio’s raw speed and Quasar’s lifetime discipline,
but only if the current unsound APIs are corrected and the developer experience is
expanded. By returning Ref/RefMut everywhere, constraining types to Pod + FixedLayout ,
harmonizing the API surface, adding compile‑time validation, finishing the CLI and IDL,
documenting unsafety and exploring innovative borrow‑stack and hybrid patterns, Hopper
can truly deliver safe, high‑performance, easy‑to‑use zero‑copy programming on Solana.
